"The realm of the Twofold Goddess is that of both light and darkness. By the light of the silver moon and the darkness of the void, you shall find sanctuary and enlightenment."

-

-

"There is wisdom in planning and forethought, but purity in decisiveness and instinct. Think first, but do not hesitate to disregard a plan if you wish it."

-

-

"Strive to discover truth in all things, but do not hesitate to shroud or obscure the truth from others when deemed necessary, as not all are deserving of the grace of knowledge."

"Tolerance is a worthy path, but there is equal worth in prejudice. Love and hate are two sides of the same coin, and it is only in embracing both that you are made whole by the Twofold Goddess."

This dusty old tome might be of great interest, if not for the fact that it is decayed beyond legibility.

This tome appears to be in pristine condition. It is titled 'The Twofold Goddess', and it details the dogma and faith of the Order of the Darkened Moon.

-

"The Twofold Goddess is light and darkness made manifest. The moon and the void, both sides of a single coin. It is only through the acceptance of this simple fact that one can hope to grasp the truth of eternity."

-

Various rituals, ceremonies and prayers are contained within the pages of the tome, and it is fairly comprehensive in it's explanation of the faith of the Twofold Goddess.

A stack of paperwork and a ledger are present on this writing desk. They appear to contain records of various transactions and messages between this chapterhouse of the Order of the Darkened Moon and numerous other groups, the identities of whom are left unknown.

The exact nature of the transactions and messages are unclear as both the paperwork and ledger appear to have been written in code.

Let all on whom Selune's light falls be welcome if they desire. As the silver moon waxes and wanes, so too does life. Trust in Selune's radiance, and know that all love alive under her light shall know her blessing. Turn to the moon, and she will be your true guide. Promote acceptance and tolerance. See all other beings as equals. Aid fellow Selunites as if they were your dearest friend.

Reveal secrets only to fellow members of the faithful. Never follow hope or turn to promises of success. Quench the light of the moon (agents and items of Selûne) whenever you find it, and hide from it when you cannot prevail. The dark is a time to act, not wait. It is forbidden to strive to better your lot in life or to plan ahead save when directly overseen by the faithful of the Dark Deity. Consorting with the faithful of good deities is a sin except in business dealings or to corrupt them from their beliefs. Obey and never speak out against ranking clergy unless it would result in your own death

Soft moonlight passes through a skylight into the chamber below, dimly illuminating the surrounding area. The sky visible through the skylight is odd, constellations not matching those of the night sky on the surface...
This pouch is full of finely-ground Belladonna.

This tapestry is tattered and moldy, but the image is still discernable.

'Five figures are depicted in the tapesty. From left to right;

 - A woman in plate-mail, a sword sheathed at her belt. Her tabard is black with a purple border, and the symbol of a silver moon dotted with purple stars is emblazoned on the cloth. She does not appear to have eyes.

 - An androgynous figure, dressed entirely in black clothes with purple trim. They are hooded, and their face is obscured entirely by a gleaming silver mask in the form of a woman's face. The mask does not possess eye-holes.

 - A male child, clothed in a sleeveless doublet of black with silver trim. His arms are bared and covered in scratches, though there is no blood. His hair is dark, his expression grim, and he does not appear to have eyes.

 - A woman in a dress of silver and gold. Her hands are hidden within her flowing sleeves, and her feet are bare. She has a peaceful smile upon her face, and her stance is relaxed. She does not appear to have eyes.

 - A man clothed in a long, pitch-black robe. The symbol of a silver cresent moon is emblazoned on his robe atop his heart. He appears to be eldery, with gray hair and a wrinkled face. He does not appear to have eyes.

The figures are standing side-by-side, 'looking' outward to the viewer. Despite the lack of eyes in all depicted figures, the viewer distinctly feels as though they are being watched.'
